## Context
The orchestrator dispatches by identifier prefix: `_fetch_one` routes
`isbn:...` values to the Libgen fetcher, and batch mode (`load_download_tasks`)
already accepts an `isbn:` prefix in the DOI column. But the single-download
convenience path (`fetch.py --doi`) runs `validate_doi`, which rejects an ISBN.
So a single book can only be fetched by invoking `fetch_libgen.py --isbn`
directly — the orchestrator has no `--isbn` entry point. Close that gap so
single-book fetches go through the same pipeline (Zotero dedup, logging) as DOIs.

## Relevant files
- `fetch.py` — `parse_args` (add `--isbn`), `handle_single_download` (route ISBN
  without `validate_doi`), `main` (trigger single mode on `--isbn`).
- `tests/test_fetch.py` — new test for the ISBN single-download route.

## Actions
1. Add `--isbn` to the orchestrator ArgumentParser.
2. In `handle_single_download`, when `--isbn` is given, build `isbn:<value>` and
   route through `_fetch_one` without calling `validate_doi`.
3. Trigger single-download mode when `--isbn` is present (alongside `--doi`/`--title`).

## Test
- `handle_single_download` with `--isbn 9780262…` dispatches to `fetch_libgen`
  (monkeypatched) and returns its result — asserted red-first.

## Verification
- [ ] `python fetch.py --isbn <isbn> --source libgen` fetches one book.
- [ ] `--doi` path unchanged; `validate_doi` still rejects malformed DOIs.

## Invariants
- Batch dispatch and the DOI single path keep their current behavior.
- `make check` (or repo test suite) passes; ruff clean.

## Exit criteria
- `fetch.py --isbn` fetches a single book through the Libgen route.
- Test covers the new route; existing tests still pass.
